<h1>Early Modern Rationalism</h1><div id="pubinfo"><em>First published Fri Apr 17, 2026</em></div>

<div id="preamble">

<p>
The expression &lsquo;rationalism&rsquo; is a historiographical
category that refers to a set of views more or less shared by a number
of philosophers active in the seventeenth and eighteenth centuries.
This period saw the heyday of metaphysical system-building, but the
expression &lsquo;rationalism&rsquo;, as the term is understood in
this entry, connotes primarily epistemological commitments. Since the
early twentieth century, &lsquo;rationalism&rsquo; has typically been
presented in contrast with &lsquo;empiricism&rsquo;. By contrast to
so-called &lsquo;empiricism&rsquo;, which traces (all) knowledge to
sensory experience, &lsquo;rationalists&rsquo; tend to rely upon the
powers of reason to explain and justify what we know.</p>

<p>
This entry provides an account of the traditional narrative of early
modern &lsquo;rationalism&rsquo; while also extending that narrative
to cover figures from typically under-represented backgrounds who hold
commitments that can also plausibly be characterized as
&lsquo;rationalist&rsquo;. The entry thus covers Ren&eacute; Descartes
(1596&ndash;1650), Baruch Spinoza (1632&ndash;1677), and Gottfried
Wilhelm Leibniz (1646&ndash;1716), alongside Anton Wilhelm Amo
(1703&ndash;1759), Margaret Cavendish (1623&ndash;1673), and Anne
Conway (1631&ndash;1679). The entry also concludes by briefly
suggesting future directions for scholarship on early modern
rationalism involving the application of rationalist principles in
topics such as social and political philosophy, as illustrated through
the writings of Sor Juana In&eacute;s de la Cruz (1645&ndash;1695) and
Fran&ccedil;ois Poulain de la Barre (1647&ndash;1723).</p>
</div> 

