 Ott 2016; Duchesneau 2023.</p>

<h3 id="InnaKnow">2.2 Innate Knowledge</h3>

<p>
The second commitment this entry identifies as a criterion for being
considered a rationalist is a commitment to the existence of innate
knowledge. This commitment holds that we have some knowledge that is
intrinsic or justified independently of experience. This section
identifies some important examples of innate knowledge and outlines
what makes innate knowledge uniquely important to each author.</p>

<h4 id="InnaIdeaDescCart">2.2.1 Innate Ideas in Descartes (and Cartesianism)</h4>

<p>
Descartes&rsquo; commitment to innate ideas is on display throughout
his works. In the <em>Third Meditation</em>, for example, Descartes
includes innate ideas, in addition to adventitious and fictitious
ideas, in his enumeration of the three kinds of ideas (AT VII
37&ndash;8, CSM II 26). In this passage, Descartes defines innate
ideas in terms of the &ldquo;understanding&rdquo; of certain things
which derives &ldquo;simply from my own nature&rdquo;. The suggestion
here seems to be that the content of innate ideas originates
independently of experience (see the entry on
 <a href="../descartes-epistemology/">Descartes&rsquo; epistemology</a>).
 In a letter to Mersenne, Descartes specifies that the content of
innate ideas consists in &ldquo;true, immutable and eternal
essences&rdquo;, such as &ldquo;God, mind, body, triangle&rdquo;. (AT
III 383, CSMK III 183)</p>

<p>
As for the innate knowledge of these essences, Descartes describes it
as &ldquo;remembering&rdquo; or &ldquo;noticing&rdquo; things that are
intrinsically contained in the mind (<em>Fifth Mediation</em>, AT VII
64, CSM II 44). Importantly, these essences are not always
&ldquo;expressly known&rdquo; by us. Rather, Descartes maintains that
this innate knowledge is achieved by &ldquo;the power of our own
native intelligence, without any sensory experience&rdquo; (Letter to
Voetius, May 1643, AT VIIIB 166&shy;&ndash;7, CSMK III 222&ndash;3).
This means that the mind &ldquo;has the faculty of summoning up&rdquo;
or, as it were, digging out the ideas of the essences which were
naturally implanted within it through the activity of reason alone
(<em>Third Set of Replies</em>, AT VII 189, CSM II 132).</p>

<p>
Descartes&rsquo; innatism can be interpreted, as suggested by Newman
(2006), in such a way that the representational content of ideas is
derived solely from the mind and its properties, independent of
sensory experience. For a discussion of the scope of innate ideas
within Descartes&rsquo; epistemology, see Flage and Bonnen 1992. On
how Descartes&rsquo; innatism may be understood as a reaction to the
scholastic perspectives of his contemporaries, see Schmaltz 1997. A
thorough examination of the topic, analyzing how innatism emerges
across many of Descartes&rsquo; works in different aspects to form the
foundation of his epistemological project, is offered by Boyle
2011.</p>

<p>
Despite their central role in Descartes&rsquo; framework, innate ideas
were rejected by two of his 17<sup>th</sup>-century followers: Nicolas
Malebranche (1638&ndash;1715) and Robert Desgabets (1610&ndash;1678).
Malebranche&rsquo;s rejection of innate ideas follows from his overall
rejection of the Cartesian account of ideas as modes of thought. His
doctrine of Vision in God holds that ideas are perfections of God
contained only in divine wisdom. Additionally, Malebranche argues that
innate ideas violate the simplicity with which God acts, since God
would have to implant an infinite stock of innate ideas in the mind
(<em>SAT</em> III.ii.4, LO 226&ndash;7).&nbsp;Desgabets, by contrast,
rejects innate ideas while remaining a proponent of the orthodox
Cartesian view of ideas as modes of thought. Desgabets subscribes to a
version of the Scholastic principle &lsquo;<em>nihil est in intellect
quod non prius fuerit in sensu</em>&rsquo; (&lsquo;nothing is in the
intellect which was not previously in the senses&rsquo;). By this
principle Desgabets understands that there can be absolutely no
operations of thought which are independent of experience. This is
because all human thought is intrinsically successive: &ldquo;all our
thoughts have a beginning, continuation, and end&rdquo; (RD 5:
189).&nbsp;For Desgabets, succession, or temporality, depends on
(local) motion, and motion is a mode of body. Therefore, all the
operations of the soul depend for their origin on the body, so that it
is only by means of sense-experience that the soul can have its
thoughts.</p>

<p>
The history of Cartesianism highlights how the ostensibly rationalist
commitments adopted by Descartes get recharacterized in new and
potentially incompatible ways.</p>

